<div id="review_3001330292" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3001330292" />
    <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour"><img alt="J.M. Hushour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442964894p2/17463213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3001330292?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.M. Hushour" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour">J.M. Hushour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3001330292" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9449727721883197685">&quot;Gilligan! Drop those coconuts!&quot;<br/><br/>I can see I&apos;m in a very slim minority here, but I&apos;m not afraid to come right out and say it: this book is terrible.<br/><br/>*Spoilers follow*<br/><br/>The five luckiest fuckers alive end up on a &quot;deserted&quot; Pacific island after their balloon crashes after escaping Confederate Richmond. Yes, you read that right. Not only are they lucky-as-hell, but even better the island happens to basically have every single natural resource that humanity could ever exploit. Even even better, one of </span>
  <span id="freeText9449727721883197685" style="display:none">"Gilligan! Drop those coconuts!"<br /><br />I can see I'm in a very slim minority here, but I'm not afraid to come right out and say it: this book is terrible.<br /><br />*Spoilers follow*<br /><br />The five luckiest fuckers alive end up on a "deserted" Pacific island after their balloon crashes after escaping Confederate Richmond. Yes, you read that right. Not only are they lucky-as-hell, but even better the island happens to basically have every single natural resource that humanity could ever exploit. Even even better, one of the castaways is The Professor from Gilligan's Island, who can invent coconut-milk powered cars but can't get them off the island. That is essentially what happens here. For 600+ pages you're treated to the more and more infuriating and insufferable excesses of the conveniently-traited castaways as they forge with ease a civilization (a convenient teenager who knows everything about plants and animals; the black guy who conveniently cooks well, etc) that would leave the Skipper envious.<br />The "mystery" crops up every 100 pages or so, so there is no tension whatsoever, you basically forget about the fact that there might be someone else on the island (the reveal the only real interesting part of the whole slog) until it's too late and you want to tear your eyes out after hundreds and hundreds of pages of clever inventiveness. <br />There is no real danger or threat. The castaways don't even have sex together, I guess because they're all men and we can't have anything interesting be addressed. No, we have to read pages of how the Professor makes nitroglycerin out of monkey urine.<br />Whatever! The troubling part is I really like Jules Verne, but I'm not sure what the hell he was trying to do here, some statement on sexless utilitarianism, maybe?</span>
  <a data-text-id="9449727721883197685" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


